wiki_catalogs.name: System Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the overall system architecture and purpose. Explain the project's mission as a professional-grade cryptocurrency trading platform with algorithmic trading capabilities integrated with OKX exchange. Document the full-stack nature of the application with Rust backend and Vue 3 frontend via Tauri. Describe the key components and their relationships, including market data processing, strategy framework, backtesting engine, trading execution, risk management, and monitoring system. Provide both conceptual overviews for beginners and technical details for experienced developers. Include practical examples of common user workflows such as strategy development lifecycle (create → validate → backtest → paper trade → deploy live) and trading operations. Document the technology stack, deployment model, and primary use cases. Address system goals, design philosophy, and architectural trade-offs.

Include information about component composition patterns, props usage, and event handling between components. Provide examples of how views interact with shared layouts and routing. Address responsive design considerations and accessibility implementation across components.

Include concrete examples from the actual codebase showing how audit trail entries are created and how they can be analyzed. Explain the relationship between the audit trail and performance metrics, particularly how the detailed trade history enables deep analysis of strategy behavior. Address configuration options for audit trail verbosity and storage. Discuss common issues like data overload and their solutions. wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the data flow throughout the system. Explain the primary data pathways: from OKX exchange through WebSocket to the Market Data Collector, through Quality Control, and into storage (TimescaleDB/Redis). Describe the flow from storage to the Strategy Framework for signal generation, then to Trading Execution with Risk Validation, and finally back to the exchange. Detail the frontend-backend communication via Tauri commands, including how UI actions trigger backend operations and how data is returned for display. Include information about data consistency, latency considerations, and error handling in data pipelines.

wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# EA OKX Quantitative Trading System - Comprehensive Project Overview

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
The EA OKX Quantitative Trading System is a professional-grade cryptocurrency trading platform built with Rust, designed to provide high-performance, type-safe, and reliable algorithmic trading capabilities. The system integrates with the OKX exchange to enable real-time market data processing, strategy development, backtesting, and automated trading execution.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- **High Performance**: Achieve low-latency trading with signal-to-market latency under 100ms (p95)
- **Type Safety**: Leverage Rust's type system to prevent runtime errors in financial calculations
- **Reliability**: Maintain 99.9% system uptime with auto-reconnection and fault tolerance
- **Comprehensive Testing**: Achieve and maintain over 90% test coverage across all modules
- **Production-Ready**: Deliver a complete system suitable for live trading operations

### Target Audience
- Quantitative traders and algorithmic trading professionals
- Cryptocurrency trading firms and hedge funds
- Individual traders seeking a robust, self-hosted trading platform
- Developers building algorithmic trading strategies

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The project follows a modular monorepo architecture with nine specialized crates, each focusing on a specific domain:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Frontend] --> B[Tauri Commands]
    B --> C[Core Models]
    B --> D[Strategy Framework]
    B --> E[Trading Execution]
    B --> F[Risk Management]
    B --> G[Backtesting]
    C --> H[OKX Client]
    H --> I[Data Layer]
    I --> J[Database]
    D --> G
    E --> F
    F --> C
    G --> C
    style A fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
    style J fill:#bbf,stroke:#333
```

### Design Patterns
The system employs several key design patterns:

- **Trait-Based Architecture**: Strategy interface using async traits for extensibility
- **State Machines**: 12-state lifecycle management for strategies and 9-state management for orders
- **Event-Driven Design**: Market data processing through event streams
- **Type-Safe Wrappers**: Newtype pattern for Symbol, Price, and Quantity with validation
- **Dependency Injection**: Tauri managed state for service integration

### System Relationships
The components interact through well-defined interfaces:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Frontend[Vue 3 Frontend] --> Tauri[Tauri Bridge]
    Tauri --> Commands[Tauri Commands]
    Commands --> Strategy[Strategy Framework]
    Commands --> Trading[Trading Execution]
    Commands --> Risk[Risk Management]
    Commands --> Backtest[Backtesting Engine]
    Strategy --> Core[Core Models]
    Trading --> Core
    Risk --> Core
    Backtest --> Core
    Core --> OKX[OKX Client]
    OKX --> Data[Data Layer]
    Data --> TimescaleDB[(TimescaleDB)]
    Data --> Redis[(Redis)]
    style Frontend fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
    style TimescaleDB fill:#bbf,stroke:#333
    style Redis fill:#bbf,stroke:#333
```

### Data Flow
The data flows through the system in a pipeline fashion:

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Exchange[OKX Exchange] --> WebSocket[WebSocket Client]
    WebSocket --> Collector[Market Data Collector]
    Collector --> Quality[Quality Control]
    Quality --> Storage[TimescaleDB/Redis]
    Storage --> Strategy[Strategy Framework]
    Strategy --> Signal[Trading Signals]
    Signal --> Execution[Order Execution]
    Execution --> Risk[Risk Validation]
    Risk --> Exchange
    style Exchange fill:#f96,stroke:#333
    style Storage fill:#bbf,stroke:#333
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- `frontend/src-tauri/src/main.rs` - Tauri application entry point
- `crates/core/src/lib.rs` - Core domain models entry point
- `crates/okx-client/src/lib.rs` - OKX client entry point
- `crates/strategy/src/lib.rs` - Strategy framework entry point

### Core Modules
- `crates/core` - Fundamental types and models
- `crates/okx-client` - Exchange integration
- `crates/data` - Data ingestion and quality control
- `crates/strategy` - Strategy development framework
- `crates/backtest` - Backtesting engine
- `crates/trading` - Order execution algorithms
- `crates/risk` - Risk management system
- `crates/monitoring` - System monitoring and alerting

### Configuration Approach
- `Cargo.toml` - Workspace and dependency configuration
- `frontend/src-tauri/tauri.conf.json` - Tauri application configuration
- Environment variables for API credentials and system settings

### External Dependencies
- `d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\Cargo.toml` - Workspace dependencies
- `d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\frontend\package.json` - Frontend dependencies

### Integration Points
- `frontend/src-tauri/src/commands/` - Tauri command integration
- `crates/core/src/models/` - Shared domain models
- Database migrations in `migrations/` directory

### Component Relationships
```mermaid
graph LR
    Core[Core Models] --> OKX[OKX Client]
    Core --> Data[Data Layer]
    Core --> Strategy[Strategy Framework]
    Core --> Backtest[Backtesting]
    Core --> Trading[Trading Execution]
    Core --> Risk[Risk Management]
    OKX --> Data
    Data --> Strategy
    Strategy --> Backtest
    Strategy --> Trading
    Trading --> Risk
    Risk --> Trading
    Monitoring[Monitoring] --> All[All Components]
    style Core fill:#f96,stroke:#333
    style Monitoring fill:#6f9,stroke:#333
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
The EA OKX system provides a comprehensive suite of features for quantitative trading:

- Real-time market data collection from OKX WebSocket
- Advanced data quality control with five validation layers
- Flexible strategy framework with hot-reload capability
- Event-driven backtesting with realistic cost models
- Sophisticated order execution algorithms (TWAP/VWAP)
- Comprehensive risk management with pre-trade validation
- REST API server for system integration
- Monitoring and alerting system

### Implementation Highlights
- **Strategy Lifecycle**: 12-state management from Draft to Archived
- **Order Execution**: 9-state order state machine with reconciliation
- **Risk Management**: Six pre-trade validators and three VaR calculation methods
- **Data Quality**: Five-layer validation pipeline with anomaly detection
- **Backtesting**: Realistic cost modeling with commission and slippage

### Feature Architecture
```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Initialization
    Initialization --> DataCollection: Start
    DataCollection --> StrategyExecution: Market Data
    StrategyExecution --> SignalGeneration: Process Data
    SignalGeneration --> RiskValidation: Trading Signal
    RiskValidation --> OrderExecution: Validated Signal
    OrderExecution --> PositionManagement: Order Submitted
    PositionManagement --> PerformanceTracking: Position Updated
    PerformanceTracking --> StrategyExecution: Metrics
    RiskValidation --> Rejected: Risk Check Failed
    OrderExecution --> Failed: Execution Failed
    style DataCollection fill:#f96,stroke:#333
    style StrategyExecution fill:#f96,stroke:#333
    style RiskValidation fill:#f96,stroke:#333
```

Sources:
- [Cargo.toml](d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\Cargo.toml)
- [package.json](d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\frontend\package.json)
- [core/lib.rs](d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\crates\core\src\lib.rs)
- [okx-client/lib.rs](d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\crates\okx-client\src\lib.rs)
- [data/lib.rs](d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\crates\data\src\lib.rs)
- [strategy/lib.rs](d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\crates\strategy\src\lib.rs)
- [backtest/lib.rs](d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\crates\backtest\src\lib.rs)
- [tauri.conf.json](d:\soft\workspace\ai\ea_okx\frontend\src-tauri\tauri.conf.json)
</blog>
